Chapter 1    Author’s purpose

In traditional penal systems, the evaluation of the punitive response is mainly
based on the classification of the individual offense and the corresponding
legal framework provided.
This approach presents a structurally static characteristic: every signif-
icant variation in criminal policy objectives normally requires a legislative
and institutional intervention.
The proposed model introduces instead a parametric perspective, in which
the overall functioning of the system is regulated through fundamental vari-
ables defined in advance.
The identification of a key parameter allows, in theoretical terms, the
equilibrium of the system to be modified without changing the overall struc-
ture of individual criminal offenses, but by directly acting on the reference
value that determines the behavior of the model.
This approach aims to transform the system from a predominantly reac-
tive and fragmented structure into a dynamic system, where objectives re-
lated to security, sustainability, and resource management can be regulated
through measurable parameters.
The hypothesis underlying the model is that part of the systemic inef-
ficiency derives not only from individual laws, but also from the difficulty
of rapidly adapting the entire system to changes in social, economic, and
demographic conditions.



Chapter 2    Introduction

This document describes a theoretical model of criminality management
based on the concept of a maximum constrained penal capacity.
The objective is to analyze a dynamic system in which the population
subject to penal restrictions is regulated through a maximum quantitative
limit (CAP), defined in relation to the general population or to a percentage
of GDP.
The model is studied as a mathematical problem of resource management,
optimization, and flow control.
The model is based on the attempt to provide complete certainty of pun-
ishment, while in situations of critical system conditions increasing severity
without creating additional costs for taxpayers.



Chapter 3   Definition of the CAP limit
The CAP, or maximum prison population threshold, would become an indi-
cator of the stability of the state itself.
Once the CAP is exceeded, the state would face a criminality problem
that could justify extraordinary interventions aimed at restoring public order.
For simplicity, the model is based on a population quota; however, a vari-
ant based on dedicated GDP expenditure could potentially be more effective.
3.1 Model variables
Let:
• Ptot = total population of the State;
• D(t) = penal population at time t;
• Dmax = maximum capacity of the system.
The main constraint is:
D(t) ≤ Dmax (3.1)
where:
Dmax = αPtot (3.2)
with:
α = 0.01 (3.3)
The model therefore assumes a theoretical maximum capacity equal to
1% of the population.



